If you want to use a `Dictionary` in C# where the key is a `Vector3` object, you can achieve this by providing a custom comparer for the `Vector3` class or using a custom class that stores `Vector3` and implements the `GetHashCode` and `Equals` methods appropriately. 

Here is an example of using a custom class as the key in a `Dictionary` where the key is a `Vector3` object:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Numerics;

// Custom class to store Vector3 and implement hashing and equality
public class Vector3Key
{
    public Vector3 Vector { get; private set; }

    public Vector3Key(Vector3 vector)
    {
        Vector = vector;
    }

    public override int GetHashCode()
    {
        return Vector.GetHashCode();
    }

    public override bool Equals(object obj)
    {
        if (obj is Vector3Key other)
        {
            return Vector.Equals(other.Vector);
        }
        return false;
    }
}

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        Dictionary<Vector3Key, string> vectorDict = new Dictionary<Vector3Key, string>();

        Vector3 vector1 = new Vector3(1.0f, 2.0f, 3.0f);
        Vector3 vector2 = new Vector3(4.0f, 5.0f, 6.0f);

        vectorDict[new Vector3Key(vector1)] = "First Vector";
        vectorDict[new Vector3Key(vector2)] = "Second Vector";

        // Access values using Vector3 as key
        foreach (var pair in vectorDict)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"Key: {pair.Key.Vector}, Value: {pair.Value}");
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the `Vector3Key` class is used to wrap the `Vector3` object and provide custom implementations of `GetHashCode` and `Equals` methods to ensure proper hashing and equality comparison. The `Vector3` objects are used as keys in the `Dictionary<Vector3Key, string>`. 

Feel free to adapt this example to suit your specific needs or if you have any further questions.

