The `count()` method in `std::chrono::duration` is used to retrieve the count of ticks in the duration. For floating-point durations like `std::chrono::duration<double>`, the `count()` method will return the count as a floating-point value of the same type as the duration.

When applied to a duration of type `std::chrono::duration<double>`, the `count()` method will return the duration value in seconds as a `double`. This allows you to extract the numerical value of the duration, which is then used to represent the time interval using the specified unit.

Here is an example demonstrating how `count()` can be used with a `std::chrono::duration<double>` to retrieve the duration value in seconds:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <chrono>

int main() {
    using FSeconds = std::chrono::duration<double>;
    FSeconds duration(5.25); // Example duration of 5.25 seconds

    // Using count() to retrieve the duration value in seconds
    double durationInSeconds = duration.count();

    std::cout << "Duration in seconds: " << durationInSeconds << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, the `count()` method is called on a `std::chrono::duration<double>` object to obtain the duration value in seconds as a `double`, which is then printed to the console.

Therefore, when you apply `count()` to a `std::chrono::duration<double>` obtained from the expression `duration_cast<utils::FSeconds>(...)`, you will receive the time difference in seconds as a `double` value.

If you print a duration object without using the `count()` method, it will represent the duration using the type of the duration itself (e.g., `std::chrono::duration<double>`). The output will not directly show the numerical value in seconds. Instead, it will show the duration object itself, which contains information about the time interval in terms of ticks.

Here is an example to illustrate printing a `std::chrono::duration<double>` object without applying `count()`:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <chrono>

int main() {
    using FSeconds = std::chrono::duration<double>;
    FSeconds duration(5.25); // Example duration of 5.25 seconds

    // Printing the duration object without using count()
    std::cout << "Duration object: " << duration << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

When you run this code and print the `duration` object without applying `count()`, the output will provide information about the duration object itself rather than directly showing the time interval in seconds. The output may include information about the tick count or the underlying representation of the duration.

For more meaningful output showing the time interval in seconds, you would typically use the `count()` method to extract the duration value as a numeric type (e.g., `double`) for display or further processing.

To add a tracker ID to the AprilTag tracker in your application, you can associate each detected AprilTag with a unique tracker ID. This ID can be used to track and identify individual tags as they move or interact within the scene.

Here is an example of how you can add a tracker ID to AprilTags:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <unordered_map>

// Tracker ID for AprilTags
struct AprilTagTracker {
    std::unordered_map<int, std::string> tagTracker; // Map to store tracker IDs for each detected tag

    void addTrackerID(int tagID, const std::string& trackerID) {
        tagTracker[tagID] = trackerID; // Assign tracker ID to a detected AprilTag
    }

    std::string getTrackerID(int tagID) {
        if (tagTracker.find(tagID) != tagTracker.end()) {
            return tagTracker[tagID]; // Retrieve tracker ID for a detected tag
        }
        return ""; // Return empty string if tracker ID is not found for the tag
    }
};

int main() {
    AprilTagTracker tracker;

    // Add tracker ID for a detected AprilTag
    tracker.addTrackerID(123, "Tracker1");
    tracker.addTrackerID(456, "Tracker2");

    // Retrieve the tracker ID for a detected tag
    int detectedTagID = 123;
    std::string trackerID = tracker.getTrackerID(detectedTagID);

    if (!trackerID.empty()) {
        std::cout << "Tracker ID for tag " << detectedTagID << ": " << trackerID << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "Tracker ID not found for tag " << detectedTagID << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this example:
- The `AprilTagTracker` struct maintains an `unordered_map` to store the association between AprilTag IDs and tracker IDs.
- The `addTrackerID` method adds a tracker ID for a detected AprilTag.
